<task id="dita-profiling-conditions-tutorial">
  <title><?oxy_comment_start author="steven_higgs" timestamp="20150505T144020+0300" comment="Change this to a topic with two sections.  The first section should be something about setting the profiling attributes and condition sets (and link to those topics listed in related links). The info in the first two steps would be included but they are incomplete.  The 2nd section would be how to use these attributes/condition sets when editing documents (the info in step 3, and more). Also see the &quot;applying&quot; related links so that it&apos;s not duplicated."?>How
    to Profile DITA Content<?oxy_comment_end?></title>
  <prolog>
    <metadata>
      <keywords>
        <indexterm>Profile DITA step by step<indexterm>conditional text<indexterm>profiling
              tutorial</indexterm></indexterm></indexterm>
      </keywords>
    </metadata>
  </prolog>
  <taskbody>
    <context/>
    <steps>
      <step>
        <cmd><ph conkeyref="reusable.menus/Open-the-preferences-page"/>, go to <menucascade>
            <uicontrol>Editor</uicontrol>
            <uicontrol>Edit modes</uicontrol>
            <uicontrol>Author</uicontrol>
            <uicontrol>Profiling / Conditional Text</uicontrol>
          </menucascade>, and edit the <uicontrol>Profiling Attributes</uicontrol> table.</cmd>
        <info>Note that this table will be ignored if a <xref
            href="../topics/subject-scheme-map.dita#topic_25s_2ph_md">Subject Scheme Map</xref> is
          in use.</info>
      </step>
      <step>
        <cmd>For DITA documents, there are already default entries for <codeph>audience</codeph>,
            <codeph>platform</codeph>, <codeph>product</codeph>, <codeph>otherprops</codeph> and
            <codeph>rev</codeph>. You can customize the attributes and their values.</cmd>
        <info>This is a one-time operation. Once you save the customized attributes and values, you
          can use them to profile any DITA project.</info>
      </step>
      <step>
        <cmd>To use the profiling attributes set in the previous step, do one of the
          following:</cmd>
        <substeps>
          <substep>
            <?oxy_comment_start author="Mark" timestamp="20141009T153551-0400" comment="This is not a procedure, but a list of alternative. But the alternative have different scopes. a is for profiling topics. b is for profiling elements."?>
            <cmd>Right-click <uicontrol
                conref="../topics/oxygen-shortcuts-list.dita#oxygen-shortcuts-list/command_click"/>
              a topic reference in <uicontrol>DITA Maps Manager</uicontrol> and choose
                <uicontrol>Edit Profiling Attributes</uicontrol> from the contextual menu.</cmd>
          </substep>
          <substep>
            <cmd>In the <uicontrol>Author</uicontrol> editing mode, right-click <uicontrol
                conref="../topics/oxygen-shortcuts-list.dita#oxygen-shortcuts-list/command_click"/>
              an XML element and choose <uicontrol>Edit Profiling Attributes</uicontrol> from the
              contextual menu.</cmd>
          </substep>
          <substep>
            <cmd>Use the <uicontrol>Attributes</uicontrol> view to set profiling
              attributes.<?oxy_comment_end?></cmd>
          </substep>
        </substeps>
        <info>Enable the <uicontrol>Show Profiling Attributes</uicontrol> option to display the
          profiling markup in the <uicontrol>Author</uicontrol> editing mode. </info>
      </step>
    </steps>
  </taskbody>
